Anonymous Sat 13 Mar 2021 21:14:48 No.37059487 Report
Quoted By:
>>37059094
I'll repeat what I said at the end of the previous.
>True, but my point is that blatant filler is a really bad habit to fall into. I'm talking on the scale of infodump worldbuilding or weapons porn in damned near anyhing with a military twinge. Can it be done, and done well enough to become unobtrusive? Yes. Should you? Consider them darlings and kill them like an Agatha Christie character.

So in your case and given your explanation, I'd write as much as you can with what you have. Call that your first draft. Go back after a few days and look where you can work in more characterization. Doesn't have to be hard. How they talk or hold themselves is sometimes all you need to punch up a scene.
As for the plot, use that break to read up on structure. I got lucky with my first long piece. The four quarters were almost the same length and fit a four part structure. But since then I keep a set of running notes and outlines while writing. It does take getting used to, but it also helps me. Those random thoughts I have while at work or even grocery shopping are just as important as my keyboard time. As those ideas add up, I can use them as mirrors or puzzle pieces. Sooner or later I have that eureka moment.
The other part is you have to finish a story to learn how to write the next one. If you don't admit you're not perfect, you'll allow writer's block to win. Step back, look at the bigger picture in your story, and attack with fresh mind/ideas

Anonymous Sat 13 Mar 2021 21:16:01 No.37059528 Report
Quoted By:
>>37059094
I feel like I could give you more specific advice if I knew which story you're working on. For general, maybe look at your story like a play by play, where certain decisions lead to decisions by other characters? Has the "antagonist" done anything recently? How do your protagonists respond? And vice versa? Is there any middle ground between what the antagonists have done before and what they plan to do at the end? You can create escalating stakes this way. Intimidation > Theft/Vandalism > Assault/Murder
>>37059023
I usually think of stuff that doesn't move the plot forward much as filler, even if it does have some kind of greater narrative purpose, ie. character development may not be too relevant for the plot itself but it's important for understanding and getting invested in the characters and their struggles.
>info dump world building, weapons porn
Those things are genre tropes of sci-fi, so I can tolerate indulging in it a little, but the former is always a dodgy alternative to more organic methods of introduction, and when the latter gets obsessive enough, I stop caring about the piece.
